dash 0.5.12, AArch64: drop the empty inline-asm reordering barrier tcc cannot parse.

error.h defines barrier() as an empty ``__asm__ __volatile__ ("": : :"memory")``
statement. It emits no instructions: it is a pure *compiler* barrier used inside
the INTOFF/INTON/FORCEINTON/RESTOREINT macros to stop an optimising compiler from
reordering memory accesses (notably the suppressint store) across the async-signal
critical-section boundary, or caching suppressint in a register.

tcc rejects the asm operand list ("AArch64 asm not implemented"), and as a
non-optimising, single-pass compiler it never reorders memory accesses across
statements and never keeps a global in a register across a sequence point. The
ordering property the barrier exists to enforce therefore already holds for any
code tcc generates, and INTOFF/INTON only ever guard same-thread async signal
delivery (no cross-core fence is involved). Defining barrier() as ((void)0)
yields a behaviourally identical binary.

--- dash-0.5.12/src/error.h.orig
+++ dash-0.5.12/src/error.h
@@ -80,7 +80,12 @@
 extern int suppressint;
 extern volatile sig_atomic_t intpending;

-#define barrier() ({ __asm__ __volatile__ ("": : :"memory"); })
+/* Upstream uses an empty inline-asm statement purely as a compiler
+ * reordering/clobber barrier around the suppressint critical sections.
+ * tcc cannot parse the asm operand list, and as a non-optimising compiler
+ * it never reorders memory accesses or caches globals in registers across
+ * statements, so the guarantee the barrier provides already holds. Drop it. */
+#define barrier() ((void)0)
 #define INTOFF \
 	({ \
 		suppressint++; \
